10. Given the ellipse $C: \frac{x^{2}}{a^{2}}+\frac{y^{2}}{b^{2}}=1(a>b>0)$ intersects the line $x=-\sqrt{2} b$ at exactly one point, point $P$ is any point on the ellipse $C$, $P_{1}(-1,0), P_{2}(1,0)$, and the minimum value of $\overrightarrow{P P}_{1} \cdot \overrightarrow{P P}_{2}$ is $\frac{a}{2}$.
(1) Find the equation of the ellipse $C$;
(2) Suppose the line $l: y=k x+m$ intersects the ellipse $C$ at two distinct points $A, B$, and point $O$ is the origin, and $\overrightarrow{O M}=\frac{1}{2}(\overrightarrow{O A}+\overrightarrow{O B})$. When the area $S$ of $\triangle A O B$ is maximized, find the range of $T=\frac{1}{\left|M P_{1}\right|^{2}}-2\left|M P_{2}\right|$.
